video_description: RFK Jr. wants “in-house” medical journals. Health and Human Services Secretary Robert F. Kennedy Jr. said Tuesday that he may bar government scientists from publishing in the world’s leading medical journals, instead proposing the creation of “in-house” publications by his agency — the latest in the Trump administration’s attacks on scientific institutions. “We’re probably going to stop publishing in the Lancet, New England Journal of Medicine, JAMA and those other journals because they’re all corrupt,” Kennedy said during an appearance on the “Ultimate Human” podcast. He also described the journals as being under the control of pharmaceutical companies. Kennedy also accused several of the agencies under the Department of Health and Human Services — including the National Institutes of Health, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the Food and Drug Administration, and the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services — of being “sock puppets” for the pharmaceutical industry. Adam Gaffney, a public health researcher and an assistant professor at Harvard Medical School, wrote in an email that “banning NIH-funded researchers from publishing in leading medical journals and requiring them to publish only in journals that carry the RFK Jr. seal of approval would delegitimize taxpayer-funded research.” The podcast episode was released soon after Kennedy bypassed the CDC and declared that his department would stop recommending the coronavirus vaccine for healthy pregnant women and children. Caption from article by Niha Masih and Amy B Wang.

video_description: Today’s my birthday, & honestly, I keep forgetting that it is. My phones been in my back pocket all day not responding to people’s sweet text messages while I run around the house, and I’m cooking dinner at home tonight awaiting my husband’s arrival from work. The past few weeks, I’ve been living in pajamas, running on very little sleep, and very much need a shower 85% of the time… but even though everything’s different, today’s truly the best birthday I can ever remember having. They say having a baby & becoming a mom changes you forever, and holy cow have I discovered the truth behind that this month. There’s no greater gift than participating in the sacred creation of life with the blessing of God’s hand upon you. There’s no better view than staring into my daughter’s big blue eyes or watching her smile in her sleep as she dreams. There’s no more intoxicating feeling than your baby girl’s tiny fingers wrapping around your own, holding on for dear life.  Everything HAS changed since meeting you face to face, my beautiful baby girl - and I couldn’t imagine a more perfect birthday than to celebrate this new me as Mom, snuggled up in pajamas together as we celebrate this beautiful, divine gift we call life. Thank you for being the greatest gift I could have ever dreamed of. 27 was by far the best year of my life, but man, do I have an amazing feeling about 28. 🎂🤍

voice_to_text: Why has Sarah Jessica Parker, even after seeing her husband cheat with her own eyes, refused to divorce him? In 1991, Sarah met Matthew Broderick and they came together because of their shared love for theater. After dating for six years, they officially got married. After marriage, the couple was very loving and welcome three children. They often attended events together and performed on Broadway. However, their marriage was not without challenges, as their relationship faced difficulties shortly after they got married. The gradually dull life after marriage made Matthew feel bored, so he secretly found several lovers. Reporters frequently caught Matthew on dates with his lover, even kissing them in bars. What's worse, he even brought his lover home for the night while Sarah was away. However, even after seeing these photos with her own eyes, Sarah refused to believe her husband had cheated. She said that unless her husband kissed another woman in front of her, she wouldn't believe the media's attempts to stir trouble. Matthew always maintained the image of a good man in front of her and the kids, which made it even harder for Sarah to leave him. Even if the whole world opposed their love, Sarah still loved Matthew. Now they have been married for almost 30 years. No matter what, we all hope Matthew will never betray Sarah again.

My brother's bad choices LED to the worst night of our lives. He started hanging out with the wrong crowd after dropping out of school. Mom was worried sick because he'd come home at 3 a m. Carrying expensive stuff he couldn't afford on his part time job. Designer clothes, new phones, gold chains. We knew something wasn't right, but he'd get angry whenever we asked. One night while he was out, I found a huge duffel bag hidden under his bed. Inside were dozens of phones still in their boxes with price tags from different stores. I knew right away they were stolen. My hands were shaking as I loaded them into my car and drove to the police. When my brother found out, he completely lost it. His face turned ghostly white. He screamed that those weren't his. He was just holding them for someone. He had to pay $25,000 to replace them. Or else. You don't understand what you've done, he kept saying, pacing like a caged animal. Three days later, mom called me, crying so hard I could barely understand her. My brother was in the hospital. They found him beaten half to death behind an abandoned warehouse, zip tied to a chair. His left leg was shattered in three places. Through tears, he told me the guys he was working for did this as a warning. They said next time would be worse. They wanted me to know exactly what would happen if I ever Lost their stuff again, he whispered. That night changed everything. My brother moved across the country to start fresh. Now he works as a youth counselor, helping kids avoid the same mistakes that almost cost him his life. He says turning in those phones saved him from an even darker path.

Showers with my 14 year old son and didn't expect him to do this to me. I am a 37 year old woman and I know what you're thinking when you hear that my 14 year old son showers with me. Right. Well, I have a good reason for it. We both share the same bathroom and bedroom. First, I hesitated to admit this online because of the looks and judgmental comments I would receive from strangers. But here it goes. It all started three years ago when my husband suddenly left us without any explanation. It was a complete shock. We had been married for over 15 years and he seemed happy. Until one day he packed his bags and disappeared. All he said to us was, I'm going to buy milk at the gas station. Be right back. He never came back. The kids were devastated, especially my youngest, Max. He clung to me more than ever, seeking comfort wherever he could find it. At night, Max would come into my room, shivering from the cold, begging for a warm blanket. As much as I wanted to send him back to his own room, I couldn't bear to see him so vulnerable. So gradually, Max moved closer to my side, eventually ending up sleeping beside me, sometimes even cuddled up to me. Over time, I began to notice that Max wouldn't leave my side during the day either, whether it was taking a shower or brushing his teeth. Max was always there, watching closely. I tried to ignore it, hoping he would outgrow it like most teenage behaviours. However, as days turned into weeks and then into months, I realised that this wasn't going away anytime soon. One night, while I was taking a shower, Max asked if he could join me. I asked why, and he said that all the kids at school say I have a level 9 gas. I don't know what that means, but I was shocked. At first I hesitated, unsure if it was appropriate or healthy. But looking at him, so small and fragile, I knew deep down that I couldn't say no. And so began our new ritual. Everything was going fine, just normal showers with mother and son. Until I dropped my soap and it fell. You can now check if there's a part two by pressing share and more!

Gave my stepmom the perfect Mother's Day gift, then watched her face as she realized what it really meant. When my dad married Cassandra, I was 11. Mom had been gone for 13 months. Melanoma that spread faster than anyone expected. One day, she was complaining about a headache, and 82 days later, I was standing at her grave in a black dress that still had the tags on. Dad waited exactly one year before bringing Cassandra home. She worked at his investment firm, client relations. Perfect teeth, blonde hair that never move. The kind of woman who wore heels to other people's barbecues. She makes me happy again, dad explained, his voice gentle but firm. I need you to try, Emily. So I tried. I helped Cassandra move in, carrying boxes of designer shoes to the closet where Mom's gardening clothes used to hang. I nodded politely when she rearranged our furniture, replacing family photos with abstract art that opened up the space. I even smiled when she transformed Mom's vegetable garden into a meditation patio, because growing our own food is so provincial. For three years, I performed the role of grateful stepdaughter. I attended her corporate events wearing the dresses she bought me. I tolerated her friends who cooed about how mature I was. For 14, I kept my grief hidden behind perfect grades and false smiles. Dad didn't notice when I stopped laughing, too busy with Cassandra's social calendar and the new clients she brought in. Too distracted by their couples retreats and wine club memberships. Meanwhile, I slept with Mom's sweater under my pillow until it stopped smelling like her. Cassandra tried. In her way. She bought me expensive birthday gifts, always things she would want. She hosted elaborate dinner parties and introduced me as our daughter to important people who never remembered my name. She even started a college fund for me, making sure everyone knew about her generosity. But when I got my period for the first time, it was Google that taught me what to do. When I had nightmares about mom dying, it was the family dog who comforted me. Breaking point came during sophomore year. I was cast as the lead in the school play, the first thing I'd felt passionate about since mom died. Opening night fell on the same evening as Cassandra's charity gala. Obviously, you'll need to skip the performance, she said, not looking up from her phone. The Richardson's are bringing their son. He's at Princeton. Connections. Emily. Dad started to object, then stopped when Cassandra placed her hand on his arm. It's just a high school play, he finally said. There will be others. I went to my room and pulled out the antique jewelry box mom had left me. Inside was her wedding ring, a lock of my baby hair, and a journal I'd never opened. Too afraid of confronting her final thoughts. That night, through tears, I read it, covered a cover most Of it was what you'd expect. Her hopes for my future memories she cherished. Advice she wouldn't be able to give in person. But the last entry, dated two weeks before she died, was different. If you're reading this, Emily, I need you to know about the safe deposit box. The key is taped inside this cover. What you find there will change everything. I'm so sorry. Key was small and silver, with the bank's name etched into it. The next day, I skipped school and went to First National. The manager recognized me. Mom's family had banked there for generations. Your mother said you'd come eventually, he said, leading me to the vault. Inside the box was a USB drive, several folders of documents, and a letter addressed to me in Mom's handwriting. My dearest Emily. It began. By now, Cassandra has probably worked her way into your lives completely. I've known about her for years. I couldn't fit what happens next in this short video. Did your parents fail you? My dad missed my graduation for a job interview. Mom promised he'd make it, but kept checking her phone anxiously during the entire ceremony. I felt my heart sink when I scanned the crowd and didn't see his face anywhere. After walking across that stage, I gripped my phone, waiting for something. No texts, no calls. Complete silence. Mom couldn't look me in the eyes. When I found her afterward, she hugged me way too tight and whispered, he really tried, sweetheart. My chest burned with anger. I couldn't hide anymore. At my graduation party, relatives kept asking about dad. Mom cycled through increasingly desperate excuses. Traffic jam, work emergency, car trouble, each lie more pathetic than the last. I watched her stumble through explanations while my shame grew deeper. My friend Jake pulled me aside and asked, you doing okay, man? I just laughed and said, he's been doing this since I was 7 years old, because it was absolutely true. He missed my championship basketball game where I scored the winning shot. Missed my debate team finals when I took first place. Even missed my 18th birthday party last year. Said he had to work late again that night. After everyone finally left, I sat alone staring at my diploma. Mom tried approaching me, but I cut her off immediately. I said, grabbing my car keys, I've heard every excuse before. I drove to my old elementary school playground and sat on the Same swing where dad used to push me before work completely consumed his life. Before he became just a distant voice sometimes heard. Coming home at 2:00am, something inside me finally broke that night. All the anger I'd bottled up for years spilled over at once. I pulled out my phone and texted him. Congratulations on showing me exactly where I rank in your priorities. Message delivered. Read immediately. When I got home after midnight, Dad's car was sitting in our driveway. I found him hunched over our kitchen table. Head.

When did you realise your parents were bad at parenting? When I turned 12, my mom handed me a credit card with my name on it. Not for emergencies, for groceries. She sat me down at our kitchen table with this massive stack of manufacturer coupon she'd been collecting and said, you're smart enough to handle the shopping now. I trust you more than myself with money. At first, I felt so incredibly grown up, walking through Walmart alone every Tuesday and Friday, pushing a full sized cart while other kids my age were begging their parents for candy. They'd stare at me like I was some kind of alien. The cashiers all knew me by name within a month. Back again, honey, Linda would say, automatically helping me reach the heavy detergent bottles on the top shelf. She started setting aside the markdown meat for me when it was about to expire. I Learned which cereals had the best protein to cost ratio, how to spot when the rotisserie chickens were about to be discount wanted. I could stretch $80 into two full weeks of meals for our family of four, and I was genuinely proud of it. I had this whole elaborate system. Mondays, I'd plan the weekly menu based on store flyers and whatever coupons we had. Tuesdays, I'd hit Walmart for the bulk items and household essentials. Fridays, I'd go to the smaller grocery store for fresh produce and whatever we'd run out of during the Week, their parents would see me in the cereal aisle comparing unit prices with a calculator, and they do these obvious double takes. One woman actually followed me around the store for 20 minutes, then approached me by the checkout. Sweetie, are you shopping for your family? She asked really gently. When I nodded and showed her my organized list with meal plans written in the margins, she looked absolutely horrified. She asked if my parents were okay, if there was an adult she could call for me. I just told her what mom always said, that I was mature for my age, and this was a good life experience that would serve me well as an adult. During parent teacher conferences in October, my teacher mentioned how I always ate the free breakfast at school, even though we technically weren't on the reduced lunch program. She's incredibly responsible for her age.

Identical twins. What's the most embarrassing situation where you've been mistaken for your twin? When my sister Tracy and I were born, our parents dressed us differently so they could tell us apart. As we grew older, we embraced being identical by pulling harmless pranks like switching seats in class or pretending to be each other at the mall. But everything changed senior year when Tracy started dating our high school star football player, Noah. I never liked Noah. He had this arrogant smirk and treated everyone like they were beneath him. He'd shove freshmen into lockers and mock the band kids during lunch. Tracy insisted he was different when they were alone, but I saw how he'd grab her arm too roughly when she talked to other guys. One night, Tracy came home with tears streaming down her face. Her sleeve was pulled up, revealing finger shaped bruises. Noah had gotten jealous when she was assigned a male lab partner. She begged me not to tell her parents, saying it was a one time thing. He'd apologized, bought her flowers, promised it would never happen again. But it did happen again and again. Each time, Tracy had a new excuse. I fell during cheerleading. I bumped into a door. I watched my confident, bubbly sister become a shell of herself. She stopped wearing her favorite crop tops, started flinching at loud noises, and came homecoming night. Tracy was supposed to go with Noah, but she had a 102 degree Fever. Our parents insisted she stay home. That's when I had an idea. I put on her dress, styled my hair exactly like hers, and went to the dance instead. Noah was waiting by the punch bowl.

What has your pet accidentally conditioned you to do? My dog, Luna, trained me to wake up at exactly 2:47 a m. Every night to let her out. And that's how I discovered my husband was poisoning me. It started when Luna was a puppy. She had the tiniest bladder and would wine at my side of the bed at the same time every night for three years. My internal clock became so precise that I'd wake up seconds before her whining started. My husband and Jake always slept through it. Heavy sleeper. He'd mumble in the morning. Lucky me. Luna would do her business quickly. Then we'd both go back to bed. It became our routine. One night, I woke up at 2:47 as usual, but Luna wasn't there. I found her in the kitchen, standing perfectly still, staring at Jake. He was at the counter with his back to me, stirring something into a glass of water. Honey, I whispered. You okay? He spun around, nearly dropping the glass. Oh, you scared me. Just getting some water. Go back to bed. But Luna wouldn't move. She kept staring at him with this intense focus I'd never seen before. Her tail was low, ears back. Not scared. Alert. What's in the glass? I asked. Just water and some antacid. My stomach's been bothering me. He drank it quickly and headed back to bed. Luna followed me upstairs, but she kept looking back at the kitchen. The next night, same Routine. I woke up at 2:47, but again, Luna wasn't by the bed. I found them in the same positions. Jake at the counter, Luna watching. This time, I stayed hidden in the doorway. Jake was crushing something with the back of a spoon. Grape powder, into a glass. He filled it with water from the tap and stirred. Then he opened the fridge and pulled out the pitcher of filtered water I drank from every morning. The pitcher I always refilled before bed. He poured the powder mixture into my water pitcher. My blood went cold. I crept back upstairs, mind racing. Luna followed silently. I've been feeling sick for months. Dizzy spells, nausea, constant fatigue. My doctor ran tests but found nothing wrong. Probably stress, she'd said. Maybe depression. Jake had been so caring, bringing me breakfast in bed when I felt too weak to get up, making sure I stayed hydrated. Drink your water, babe. You need fluids. The next morning, I pretended to drink from the pitcher, but poured it down the sink when he wasn't looking. By afternoon, I felt better than I had in weeks. That night, I set my phone to record and hit it on the kitchen counter. At 2:47, Luna and I crept downstairs. Same scene. Jake crushing pills, mixing powder, contaminating my water. This time, I could see the pill bottle. Ambien. My prescription sleep aids that I'd stopped taking months ago because they made me too groggy. But the Bottle was still full. I checked last week. He'd been refilling it, getting extra pills somehow. Crushing them into my water. Every night while I slept. I watched him pour the mixture into my pitcher, then add something else. A small. A vial of clear liquid. My hands shook as I filmed Luna pressed against my leg, solid and warm. Jake sealed the vial and tucked it behind the coffee maker. Then he rinsed the glass and spoon, wiping everything clean. After, he went upstairs. Retrieve the vial. No label. I photographed everything and took the vial to hide in my car. The next day, I called my doctor. I need a blood test. Test for everything. She found traces of zolpidem and ethylene glycol in my system. Sleeping pills and antifreeze. This is attempted murder, she said quietly. We need to call the police. I'd been slowly dying for months. Symptoms? Dizziness, nausea, confusion, or textbook antifreeze poisoning. Jake had been increasing the dose gradually, making it look like a mysterious illness. The life insurance policy he'd convinced me to increase six months ago suddenly made sense. Police arrested Jake that evening. They found more vials hidden in his toolbox in the garage. Enough antifreeze to kill me three times over. In his phone, they discovered internet searches. How long does antifreeze poisoning take? Undetectable poisons, life insurance waiting periods. He'd been planning this for over a year. Luna had known something was wrong long before I did. Dogs, Can smell chemical changes in their owners. She'd been trying to protect me the only way she knew how. By making sure I was awake when he was poisoning me.

When are you going to get a real degree? Jake just stared at his plate. The kids working two jobs to pay for school. Emma kept going. She asked my cousin about her starter apartment and wondered when she'd get a grown up job. She even made a comment about Dad's old truck in the driveway, saying it was embarrassing. The whole time, my nephew Tyler was just sitting there eating his Turkey and Watching Tyler's Jake's six year old son. Super quiet kid, usually just plays with his food and doesn't say much during adult conversations. Emma was on a roll. Jake's face turned red. Mom literally gasped. Dad put down his fork and just stared at Emma. But Tyler. Back from my business trip earlier than expected. I didn't tell anyone I was returning. I wanted to surprise Miguel. When I arrived on our street, I saw several cars parked in front of our house. The garden was decorated with blue and pink balloons. A banner read welcome our little miracle. I parked my car a street away and walked over. The door was slightly open. Music and laughter spilled from inside. When I stepped in, I froze in the middle of the living room. Carmen, my best friend, was visibly six months pregnant. My mother in law, Rosa, was gently stroking her belly while my mother served drinks. Gifts were stacked on a decorated table. So is the nursery ready? My aunt Elena asked. Almost, Carmen replied. Miguel insisted on painting it himself. He's been working on it every weekend. At that moment, my husband walked in, carrying more drinks. He approached Carmen and hugged her from behind, placing his hands on her belly. We just need to set up the crib. We picked it out together last week. I watched as my mother stiffened upon seeing me. Twenty. Eight year old woman. And when I was 13, my parents left me at a gas station to teach me a lesson. They never imagined I'd take that lesson seriously. It happened during one of those long, sticky summer road trips. The van was packed. Two siblings, a cooler full of melting sandwiches, my dad's country music playing just a little too loud. We were somewhere in the middle of nowhere. A stretch of cracked road framed by flat fields and heat shimmer. I asked for water, and my mom told me to run inside and grab a bottle. I hopped out, jogged into the gas station, found a cold bottle from the fridge, and walked to the counter with a couple of crumpled bills. I remember thinking I'd beat my siblings back to the van. I actually smiled. But when I stepped outside, the van was gone. At first I waited on the curb. Five minutes and 10. I walked around the side of the building, thinking maybe they pulled up to the air pump or went around the back. Nothing. I checked inside again. Still nothing. The cashier asked if I was okay. I told him my parents were probably just messing with me. I waited 30 minutes on that metal bench outside the door. Then an hour. The sun moved, shadows shifted, and the cars that came and went were never the right one. Cashier let me use the phone behind the counter. I dialed home. No answer. I tried my mom's cell, then my dad's. I left a voicemail. Another hour passed. The cashier called the local pool police. When the officers showed up, I gave them everything I could remember. Full names, our street address, what the van looked like, what everyone was wearing. One of the officers stayed with me while the other made a few calls. They offered me a juice from the mini fridge while I waited. Six hours after I'd been left there, my parents pulled back into the lot. No speeding, no panic. They parked like they were stopping for fuel. My mother stepped out first, adjusted her sunglasses, and asked the officers what the big deal was. She told them it was discipline, that I'd been acting out, and they thought I needed a wake up call. A reminder of what happens when you're careless or forget to follow directions. My father just nodded along, arms crossed. The police didn't press charges. They said it was a parental overreaction, but that no law had technically been broken. They warned my parents not to do anything like that again. I sat in the backseat of the van the whole drive home, silent. No one said anything to me. My brother laughed the next morning and said I looked like a scared puppy. When they finally picked me up, my sister rolled her eyes and told me to stop being dramatic. At school that fall, I didn't tell anyone what Happened. I just became quiet, focused. I turned in my assignments early, stayed out of group activities, ate lunch alone when I could. I stopped expecting birthday cakes or bedtime hugs. I stopped expecting anything, really. I started preparing quietly. I kept granola bars in my backpack, just in case. Learned how to open my bedroom window from the outside using a fork. I began hiding emergency cash in an old DVD case. I didn't know what I was preparing for. I just knew I needed to be ready for the next time I was left behind. We never spoke about the gas station again. Not even once. It became one of those family moments that got edited out like a bad photo. Everyone moved on except me. I never really had a choice. When I turned 18, I applied to every out of State College I could afford the application fee for. I got into one six states away. I packed everything I owned into two suitcases and left the morning after graduation. No party, no photos. No one helped me load the cab. My mother was watering her plants when I left. My father didn't look up from the television. I moved into a dorm with strangers and never went back. Over the years, I built something for myself. It wasn't perfect, but it was mine. A job I earned without any referrals. An apartment I furnished, one thrifted chair at a time. Friends who hugged hello and remembered My birthday. People who noticed when I was quiet and asked if I was okay. No one ever left me standing alone in a parking lot. I didn't cut my parents off completely. I didn't block their numbers. I didn't change mine. But I never called. I never messaged first. The last time I saw them was three years ago at a cousin's wedding. They smiled like everything was normal. Like I hadn't spent hours alone at 13. Wondering if I'd been kidnapped or forgotten. And now, 15 years later, something's happened. Something big. Something that dragged them back into my life. After all this time, they're about to learn what it really feels like to be left behind for good. Last week, I got a call from my mother. It came through in the middle of a work day. I saw

Poor people who have dated rich people. What did you learn? When I started dating William, I didn't know his family owned half the expensive restaurants in our city. I was a waitress at a diner, making minimum wage, living in a tiny studio apartment with a broken heater. On our first date, I suggested we meet at my usual coffee spot. He showed up in a Tesla, looking completely out of place among the regular customers with their chipped mugs and laptop chargers. I noticed right away how he kept touching everything with his sleeve pulled over his hand. When I asked if he wanted to split a muffin, he politely declined, saying he wasn't hungry. Later, I found out he'd never eaten at a place that didn't have at least one Michelin star. Despite our differences, we clicked. He was funny, smart, and genuinely interested in my life. He didn't act superior when I told him about my community college classes or my dreams of opening my own bakery someday. everything changed when he invited me to his family's monthly dinner. I spent two weeks tips on a dress from a consignment shop. It was navy blue with tiny pearls on the collar, the nicest thing I'd ever owned. When I arrived at their mansion, the maid who opened the door looked more expensive than me. William's mother took one look at my dress and said, oh, darling, is that vintage? How sustainable of you. The dinner Was a nightmare. They had five different forks, and I used the wrong one for my salad. William's sister asked what my parents did for a living. When I explained that my mom worked at Walmart and my dad wasn't in the picture, she choked on her wine. But where did you summer as a child? He asked, completely serious. Then came the incident that changed everything. William's mother announced that their chef had prepared a special truffle risotto. I took one bite, and my throat started closing up. Turns out they'd use some fancy mushroom I was severely allergic to. Didn't have my Epipen because I'd never encountered it at any place I could actually afford to eat. William rushed me to the hospital in his Tesla. While I was still on the journey, his mother swept in, wearing her designer coat. Instead of asking if I was okay, she pulled William aside, and I heard her whisper, darling, if she can't even handle proper cuisine, how will she survive the Governor's Ball? That's when William surprised everyone. He turned to his mother and said, actually, Nancy makes the best chocolate souffle I've ever tasted. Better than your chefs. Mother gasped like he'd slapped her. She's been teaching me to bake, he continued. I'm investing in her bakery idea. And if you can't handle that, we won't be at any of your balls. His mother stormed out. Later that night, still in my hospital gown, William confessed something he'd Been taking secret baking lessons at a community center. Because he wanted to understand my passion. He showed me videos on his phone. Him covered in flour, burning cookies, setting off smoke alarms. Three years later, our bakery, Humble Crumbs, is the most popular spot in town. We serve both two dollar cookies and two hundred dollar wedding cakes. William's mother still won't eat here, but his sister became our biggest customer. She even admitted our five dollar muffins taste better than the fifty dollar ones at her country club. The best part? We still use those chipped mugs from our first date coffee shop. I bought their whole set when they were going out of business. William doesn't use his sleeve to touch them anymore. Last week, a food critic called our place unpretentiously perfect. William framed the review right next to my old consignment shop dress.

What was a loophole that you found and exploded the hell out of? My university had this stupid rule where we couldn't have pets in our dorms, not even fish. The punishment was a 500 dollar fine and immediate removal of the animal. But my therapy cat, Luna, helped with my anxiety attacks. I wasn't about to give her up. Barbara, our dorm supervisor, was absolutely obsessed with enforcing this rule. She done random room checks for 15 years and bragged about confiscating over 50 pets. She even kept a wall of photos in her office showing all the contraband animals she'd caught, like some twisted trophy collection. My first week, she caught someone with a hamster and made this huge show of calling animal control. While the poor girl sobbed, Barbara just stood there smirking, telling everyone, rules are rules, dear. I knew I had to be smart about keeping Luna, so instead of just sneaking her in, I spent three days reading every single page of the university's housing policies. Most of it was boring stuff about noise levels and trash disposal. But on page 43, I found exactly what I needed. No pets or animals are permitted in university housing facilities unless specifically required for documented medical conditions. The keyword was documented. Nowhere did it specify who needed to do the documenting. So I went to my regular therapist and got her to write an official letter stating that Luna was essential for managing my anxiety. I Also printed out research papers about the benefits of emotional support animals. When Barbara burst into my room during a random inspection and saw Luna, her eyes lit up like she just won the lottery. Well, well, what do we have here?

voice_to_text: What happens if a chain smoker quit smoking? Suddenly, day one without cigarettes and my body declared war on me. I've been smoking since I was 15. Half my life spent inhaling roughly 14,600 packs. That 292,000 cigarettes. At five minutes per cigarette, I'd spent nearly three years of my life just smoking. The decision wasn't dramatic. No cancer diagnosis or ultimatum. Just a moment when I watched my five year old daughter pretend to smoke a crayon, holding it exactly how I hold my marl bros. Right down to the way she flicked imaginary ash. What are you doing, Emma? I asked, already knowing I'm being you, daddy, she said, taking another pretend drag. I quit that night. Flushed the cigarettes, deleted my smoke break alarms and told no one. Previous attempts had failed when announced, like my brain needed an audience for its surrender. By 10:00am Wednesday, my hands trembled so badly I spilled coffee across my keyboard. My coworker noticed. Hangover? He asked. Quitting smoking, I admitted. His eyebrows shot up. Cold Turkey. Jesus, Mark, that's like jumping out of a plane without checking if your parachute works. By afternoon, the headache arrived. Not dull, but primal, like my skull was being crushed in a vice. Every sound became weaponized. The office printer might as well have been a jackhammer beside my ear. That night, I dreamt of cigarettes. Not just smoking them, I was swimming through to them. Thousands floating in a sea of tobacco. Each One calling my name. Day two brought rage, pure, irrational fury that made me snap at Emma for dropping her spoon at breakfast. It's just a spoon, I shouted immediately, horrified at myself. Her little face crumpled. My wife Jen took her to school instead of me. Get it together, she whispered. Call your doctor. My doctor prescribed nicotine patches, which felt like cheating, but also like survival. Your brain is literally rewiring itself, he explained. The receptors that have been flooded with nicotine for years are screaming for it. Day three. The insomnia was so bad I hallucinated. My mouth produced saliva like I was about to vomit. Constantly. Food tasted like wet cardboard. I found myself standing outside a gas station at 2 a m. Staring at the cigarette ads. Making a teenager exiting looked at me with concern. You okay, Mister? I wasn't, but I didn't buy cigarettes. Day 5 brought the dreams again. I dreamt I was smoking and woke up with crushing guilt, patting the bed for cigarette burns before realizing it wasn't real. The physical symptoms were brutal, but nothing compared to the psychological warfare. Every stress trigger felt like neon signs flashing S M O K E N O W. Day 7. Could suddenly smell everything. My co workers Cologne from across the room, the garbage from inside the house while I was still in the driveway. The lingering smoke in my car upholstery that I've been nose blind to for years. I Deep cleaned my car that weekend, gagging at the yellow residue that came off the windows. Day 14. I could climb the stairs without sounding like I was dying. My daughter noticed. Daddy, you're not making the scary breathing anymore. Day 30. The craving still ambushed me, but less frequently. I gained 8 pounds, but my skin had lost its grayish tint. My wife kissed me one morning and paused. Your mouth tastes friend, she said. Better. Day 60. I found an old jacket with a forgotten pack in the pocket. Instead of excitement, I felt revulsion. I showed my wife, who watched nervously as I crushed each one under the faucet. I didn't think you'd actually do it this time, she admitted. Neither did I, I confessed. It's been six months now. The money I've saved, nearly $2,000, paid for Emma's first real bicycle and a weekend away with my wife. My persistent cough disappeared. Food tastes incredible. Sometimes I still reach for cigarettes that aren't there. Phantom limb syndrome, but for addiction. But when Emma hugged me yesterday and said, you smell nice, daddy, instead of wrinkling her nose and pulling away, I knew with absolute certainty I would never smoke again. The war isn't over, but for the first time, I'm winning.

What's the moment that made you decide being nice wasn't working anymore? I used to be the person everyone called when they needed something. The one who would drop everything to help a friend move or stay late at work to finish someone else's project. My boss would text me at 11 p m. And I'd respond immediately. I'd cover shifts when co workers called in sick. I'd volunteer for the projects nobody wanted. I was raised to believe kindness would always come back to you. For five years at Davidson Media, I was the first to arrive and last to leave. I helped my co workers meet their deadlines. I brought coffee for the team when everyone was stressed. I even let my boss, Diane, take credit for my ideas during presentations because she said it would look better coming from management. When my dad got sick last year, I asked Diane if I could work remotely two days a week so I could drive him to chemo. She sighed and said, we really need you in the office, but I suppose we can make it work for a month or two. I was so grateful that I worked twice as hard on my office days, making sure nothing fell through the cracks. Dad's treatment was supposed to last six months, but after three months, Diane called me into her office. She said the remote arrangement wasn't working. The team needed me physically present every day. And besides, it Had been long enough. I explained that dad was only halfway through treatment. He couldn't drive himself and had no one else. She just stared at me until I lowered my eyes and said, I understand. I spent the next week burning through my savings to hire drivers for dad. I was exhausted, constantly worried about him, but still the first one in the office every morning. Then came the Maxwell Project, a huge account that could make or break our quarter. I spent weeks researching, building the pitch, creating mockups, everything. I even missed one of Dad's appointments to finish it. The day before the presentation, Diane asked to see my materials. I handed over everything, including my presentation notes. The next morning, I arrived early, excited to present my work, only to find the conference room already full. Diane was at the head of the table, showing my slides to the clients. I stood in the doorway, frozen as she used my exact words. My research, my ideas. When she saw me, she smiled and said, oh, good. Jennifer, can you grab coffee for everyone? We're just getting started. The client turned, saw me, and said, aren't you presenting this? Before I could answer, Diane jumped in and said, oh, no, this is my project. Jennifer just helped with some research. I got the coffee. I stood in the back of the room and watched as she was praised for my work. The client loved it. They signed A three year contract, the biggest in company history. When the executives came down to congratulate the team, Diane accepted all the praise. She got a bonus, she got a promotion. I got a fifty dollar gift card to Starbucks. That night, dad called. He'd fallen trying to get from the taxi to his front door. He had been lying on the ground for 20 minutes before a neighbor found him. If I had been there. I kept thinking, if I had just been there. Two days later, the company held a Celebration for the Maxwell deal. Diane was given an award. I stood and clapped with everyone else. Then came the announcement that made everything stop. Diane would now head up a new division created specifically for the Maxwell account. And she needed a strong team. She spent 10 minutes talking about the qualities she was looking for, then announced her first hire. Ryan. The guy who had been with the company for six months and hadn't contributed a single thing to the project. I sat there stunned as everyone congratulated him. Then Diane looked at me and said, Jennifer, I need those quarterly reports by end of day. I know you won't let me down. Something broke inside me. Five years. Five years of saying yes, of staying late, of missing time with my sick father. Five years of watching others take credit for my work. Five years of being nice. When did you realize your parents were bad at parenting? When I was 11, my mom would drop me off at the local mall every weekend with $15 and her credit card for emergencies only. She called it our arrangement. She got me time and I got independence training. The first few Saturdays, I thought I was the luckiest kid alive. Freedom, a food court and the arcade. I'd stretch that $15 by getting the free pizza samples and spending hours at GameStop. This college age employee, Marcus, noticed me hanging around every weekend. Back again, buddy, he'd say. Then let me play the display consoles longer than other kids. By my fourth solo Saturday, I had a routine. I knew which restaurants gave the biggest samples, which bathrooms were cleanest, and where to sit to charge my phone. I'd text mom updates like she asked, but she rarely responded until pickup time. This older security guard, Officer Ray, started appearing wherever I went. One rainy Saturday, when the mall was nearly empty, he sat down across from me in the food court. Your mom works nearby? He asked casually. I nodded, repeating the line she taught me. She's at important meetings. I'm old enough to handle myself. He studied me for a moment, then slid me his half finished pretzel. My shift ends in an hour. I can never finish these. What started as occasional Saturdays became every weekend, then extended to Friday nights, too. Mom would text last Minute. Can you handle dinner at the mall? Use the emergency card. Love you. I'd watch movies alone, sitting between families so I wouldn't look weird. Once, a dad offered me some of their popcorn, thinking I'd been separated from my parents. The kindness made my throat tight. The worst day was when I got food poisoning from day old sushi. I was violently sick in the public bathroom. A woman called mall security when she heard me crying in the stall. Officer Ray found me curled on the floor. He helped me clean up and took me to the security office, where they called my mom 17 times. No answer. They finally reached her four hours later. He was at a spa retreat three hours away. Can he just take an Uber home? She asked them. The mall manager had seen me alone too many times. He showed Officer Ray footage of me wandering alone from opening till closing, Friday nights through Sunday evenings for six straight weekends. I remember Officer Ray's face hardening as he watched. When my mom finally arrived the next morning, she brought me a milkshake like everything was fine. The security office had called child services. Mom kept saying he's mature for his age and kids need independence these days. The case worker just kept writing in her note. I spent that summer with my grandparents while mom had supervised visitation and therapy. During family counseling, we discovered she'd been dating a married man. Those weekend

The funniest way you've proved a teacher wrong. I recently turned in my English essay, and the next day, my teacher called me up to her desk. I was feeling pretty good. I actually put effort into this one. Maybe she was going to compliment my writing. Nope. She folded her hands, looked at me like a detective about to crack a case, and said, there's no way you wrote this. I laughed, thinking she was joking. She wasn't. She picked up my paper and pointed at a word. Ubiquitous. I nodded, yeah. She narrowed her eyes. You don't even know what that means. Now I knew this wasn't about my essay anymore. This was personal. I calmly defined the word, used it in three different sentences, and even threw in a synonym for extra credit. She crossed her arms. Okay, you must have used AI to write this. What? First I was too dumb to know big words. Now I was too smart to have written this myself. She made me run my essay through an AI detector. It came back 100% human written. At this point, I had proved her wrong twice, but she still would not back down. She tapped her desk, pretending to think, then went, then you must have copied this from another essay. I couldn't believe it. I literally wrote this from scratch, but now I was being accused of plagiarism. I told her to run it through a plagiarism checker. I did, and I passed. I sat back, arms crossed. Now, surely she'd apologize. She sighed, looked me in the eyes, and handed me my paper with a big fat zero written at the top. I stared at it. Wait, so what's the reason now? She shrugged. I just don't believe you. At that point, I was done. I stood up, walked to the door, and before I left I turned around, looked her dead in the eyes, and said, you know what's really ubiquitous? Your terrible grading. Then I walked out with my zero and my dignity.

What's the most painful thing you were wrongfully accused of? I was a lunch lady at Westwood Middle School for 15 years. The kids called me Miss Rosa, and I knew every single one by name. I knew who was allergic to peanuts, who needed extra portions because they didn't get enough at home, and who was having a bad day just by the look in their eyes. Every Friday, I baked chocolate chip cookies from my grandmother's recipe. It was my small way of giving the kids something to look forward to at the end of the week. The principal knew about it and always grabbed one for himself. Then came that awful Monday in October. Three students and two teachers called in sick with terrible stomach pain. By Tuesday, 15 more kids were out. The school nurse called it a stomach bug, but by Wednesday, the health department was involved. I was serving lunch when the principal and two men in it's came into the cafeteria. They asked me to step into the office. That walk felt like a mile long with all the kids watching. Your Friday cookies, the health inspector said, showing me pictures of children in hospital beds. They tested positive for rat poison. My knees gave out. I collapsed into a chair, my mind racing. How could this happen? I had made those cookies the same way for years in my own kitchen. They suspended me on the spot, took my keys, my badge, Everything. I wasn't allowed to talk to anyone from the school while they investigated. The local newspaper ran a front page story. School lunch lady poison students. They printed my picture and everything. My phone rang constantly with angry parents. Someone threw eggs at my house. My neighbour of 12 years asked me to stop waving to her children. The worst part was knowing those kids thought I had tried to hurt them. Kids who trusted me to feed them every day. Two weeks later, police showed up at my apartment with a search warrant. Therapists, what's your biggest I know I'm not supposed to judge, but holy crap moment? I had an entire family come to my office once because their daughter attempted to Hannah Baker themselves. The father and mother explained to me that long before they ever had their kids, they had only wanted boys. They believed that raising boys would have been a lot easier and were risk free because they couldn't get pregnant. Having a girl to them meant a lot of attention, arguments, and too many hormones to worry about. So. So they actually got pretty lucky and had three boys up until their last child. They found out that their fourth child was going to be a girl and attempted to abort her immediately. The abortion pill ended up failing, and they had a baby girl. When I asked the mother and father why they would even try to abort their baby, since that would have gone against their Christian values, they argued that their baby surviving was proof that she was a devil spawn and was sent as punishment to their family and the world. Their daughter, however, was actually the sweetest girl in the world. She's 10 years old and grew up knowing what her parents thought of her. For her entire life, she never felt love and was told that she was a mistake that couldn't be removed. She always felt like she shouldn't have been alive, so she tried to take matters into her Own hands. She did things to herself I'd rather not say, in an attempt to remove herself from the equation. When her family brought her to the hospital, they told her during her entire recovery process that she proved their point by being an attention seeker. Since her stunt, she's been completely absent from school and refused to leave her bed. So her father told her that they would take her to therapy, which she became excited about until she realised that meant the entire family had to go. Her father and mother repeatedly cried to me asking why their daughter was such a screw up and why she was wasting her life away. I told them they were insufferable idiots and were immediately going to be reported to CPS, that I was going to personally see to it that they'd be arrested. They told me that they knew they shouldn't have gone to therapy since it was a bunch of hippie mumbo jumbo. If not for therapist laws, I would have adopted that poor girl myself and saved her from her cult of a family. After a couple of days, a social worker was sent to their home and investigated the home where they found pictures upon pictures of their daughter. Her room was clean and the fridge was stocked with her favourite foods. The social worker was suspicious and sat the girl aside and asked if she felt safe. She admitted that they changed everything up to look Good. So they wouldn't be frowned upon by their church. She then asked to leave and was soon placed in foster care. Alicia, if you're out there reading this, I hope you're loved. Now, sweetie.

What's the most painful thing you were wrongfully accused of? I was a lunch lady at Westwood Middle School for 15 years. The kids called me Miss Rosa, and I knew every single one by name. I knew who was allergic to peanuts, who needed extra portions because they didn't get enough at home, and who was having a bad day just by the look in their eyes. Every Friday, I'd bake chocolate chip cookies from my grandmother's recipe. It was my small way of giving the kids something to look forward to at the end of the week. The principal knew about it and always grabbed one for himself. Then came that awful Monday in October. Three students and two teachers called in sick with terrible stomach pain. By Tuesday, 15 more kids were out. The school nurse called it a stomach bug, but by Wednesday, the health department was involved. I was serving lunch when the principal and two men in suits. I'm into the cafeteria. They asked me to step into the office. That walk felt like a mile long with all the kids watching. Your Friday cookies, the health inspector said, showing me picture. There's of children in hospital beds. They tested positive for rat poison. My knees gave out. I collapsed into a chair, my mind racing. How could this happen? I had made those cookies the same way for years in my own kitchen. They suspended me on the spot, took my keys, my Badge. Everything. I wasn't allowed to talk to anyone from the school while they investigated. The local newspaper ran a front page story. School lunch lady poison students. I printed my picture and everything. My phone rang constantly with angry parents. Someone threw eggs at my house. My neighbor of 12 years asked me to stop waving to her children. The worst part was knowing those kids thought I had tried to hurt them. Kids who trusted me to feed them every day. Two weeks later, police showed up at my apartment with a search warrant. They tore through everything. My clothes, my photo albums. Even my grandmother's recipe box. They took

My parents got my older brother Alexis for his 18th birthday and got me the cheapest car they could find on mine. So my grandparents threw them a humiliation party and made all relatives hate them. My brother got a car for his 18th birthday. Not a new car or anything, it was a 20 year old Lexus that was in pretty good shape and he rubbed it in my face for the rest of the time. He was in his senior year of high school. Compared with my brother, I get just as good grades as he does. Better in some cases even. I worked my hardest in the hope of fairness. I even volunteered to clean up garbage in my local area. Then. My 18th birthday came and went a few weeks ago and the only thing I wanted, the only thing I was hoping for, was a car. I wasn't expecting something like a new car or a sporty car, just something reliable like my brother got. The party was different from my brother's 18th. For his 18th birthday my mom baked the cake herself. It was a delicious layered chocolate pudding cake. I got a sheet cake from the supermarket for his. They got a DJ for me. It was my dad's old boombox with a couple of mix CDs. We went through the whole party and my parents might have just been waiting to spring a surprise gift on me, but that didn't happen as Things were wrapping up. I asked them why there was no car when my brother got one, and they said that they felt like he worked harder for it. I wondered what he did that I didn't do, because I did all of that and more. My grandma was nearby and heard everything. And then she asked them why as well. She lectured my parents that she was very disappointed in them for showing favoritism. Then she announced to everyone still there that my parents thought getting their first born son a car and DJ was fine, but not their second. And then she even pointed out how much harder my parents tried for my brother's 18th birthday than they had for mine.

The easiest way you've ever made money. Last month I was riding my bike when I spotted two women on the street screaming at each other, pulling hair, the whole dramatic scene. I pulled over, parked my bike, and leaned against a lamp post to watch. Out of nowhere, a guy in a sleek black BMW tapped my bike with his bumper, locked eyes for a moment before he smirked and said, you stopped to watch too, huh? I laughed. Looks like we both got front row seats. Instead of arguing, we turned our attention back to the chaos, squinted at the woman in the red dress, and said, I'm putting my money on her. She looks scrappy. I shook my head. Nah, the one in jeans has that crazy, unhinged energy. She's got this. He nodded. All right. A pack of smoke says I'm right. I fished a half empty pack of cheap cigarettes from my pocket and we shook on it. Few minutes later he went to his car, came back with two beers, and we cracked them open while the fight raged on. Then, just as expected, the woman in jeans threw a wild punch, sending the red dress lady straight to the pavement. Then a traffic cop rolled up, noticing his bumper still touching my bike. What's going on here? He asked. The guy just shrugged. Little tap. We're handling it. Before we left, he handed me $200 and said, for the bike, man. Thing is, My bike wasn't even that messed up. $20 was all it took to fix. A few days later, I got a text from him. Another fight downtown. Drink, smokes. And just like that, I've got a new fight watching, Buddy.
